title: For Sale/Trade:  Egyptian 8mm Hakim Semi-Auto rifle
location: King of Prussia, Southeastern, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent: Up for sale/trade is a 1950s Egyptian semi-auto rifle chambered in 8mm Mauser.  This is an example of the first firearm mass produced in Egypt - "Hakim" means "firstborn."  The Hakim is based off of a Swedish design modified to accept the 8mm Mauser round.  The Egyptians had a ton of 8mm left over from when the Germans held N. Africa in the early 1940s.  Also included is the sling (aftermarket surplus) and a gas port adjustment tool.  The rifle uses a direct gas impingement system similar to the M16/AR-15 rifles, with the inclusion of a valve in the system that can be manually adjusted to control the amount of gas that is used to cycle the bolt.  The rifle has a detachable 10 round box magazine that can be fed by stripper clips.  The rifle will accept modified German 30 round magazines and a bayonet, though I have neither.  Prefer FTF in SEPA.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Bull Barrel 16" DPMS AR15
postcontent:
MagPul MOE Stock FDE, Angled Foregrip, MIAD pistol grip, Rail covers, free-float quad rail, Cobra Tactical 45 degree canted BUIS, a railed gas block, and a cheap, but solid UTG BiPod. GG&G Agency Single point attachment can be included if you want it. CeraKoted GI mag w/ MagPul anti-tilt follower in FDE. I'll throw in a Polymer mag as well.

The factory upper was changed out with a slick sided upper, the original gas block for a railed one (no idea why I did that), and the factory barrel shroud for a no-name free floating rail system. I wanted room for an angled foregrip AND the bipod.

These rifles are inherently accurate usually grouping 1-1.5 MOA with American Eagle range ammo. I used to shoot gophers/prairie dogs in New Mexico out to 200 yards in the desert without magnification. Round count is probably more than 500, but less than 1000. Weapon was field stripped each time I shot it and properly cleaned (even better than when I pulled armory duty). Barrel is 0.936" in diameter, is crowned, no flash hider, non-threaded, 1:9 RoT. Very amusing to shoot at dusk.

This rifle is most as home shooting close and accurately, or further away with some magnification. It would be a great candidate for a Nikon 223 type optic or a Leupold Mark AR scope. Currently, I have a Burris Fix 5x AR-536 on it and it works fine. If you wanted a no frills predator or varmint gun, this one will fit the bill.

I'll consider trades, and I'll consider offers if you want it WITH the optic I have as well. I'll answer any written offer. Be local or close enough to make a drive reasonable.

title: For Sale:  Noreen -- s 338 Lapua - Picatinny forend rail
postcontent:
NOREEN BAD NEWS .338 LAPUA !!!!

Noreen has created the ONLY SEMI-AUTOMATIC .300 WIN MAG and .338 Lapua on the market. The BAD NEWS is a custom-made AR-style rifle that is chambered in the increasingly popular 338 Lapua as well as the powerful 300 WIN MAG. These cartridges give you much greater velocity and power than the typical .308, and as far as ballistics are concerned, the BAD NEWS rifle is going to be the flatter shooting gun for long range shots.

The BAD NEWS rifle is a piston-driven semi-auto; this means you can expect greater range and a higher level of reliability by running a cleaner and cooler rifle. The muzzle break on these Noreen’s significantly suppresses recoil. Additionally, the semi-auto nature of the rifle will naturally recoil less than a bolt action because part of the felt recoil is going to chamber the next round. Lighter recoil is a huge advantage when you’re looking for a rifle with a faster and more accurate follow-up shot.

This piston-driven system is unlike any other AR-10 on the market. The piston movement is strictly in the action, after the bullet has already left the barrel. This is a huge advantage on a precision rifle compared to conventional piston driven setups found in standard AR's. In those rifles, an LWRC REPR, POF P308, etc. the piston runs parallel to the barrel and moves while the bullet is still in the barrel creating unwanted barrel harmonics which adversely affect accuracy. This rifle's piston is located in the receiver and not along the barrel so the bullet is out of the barrel by the time the piston is working to chamber another round and keep your action cool and clean with no gas ever entering the action.

The semi-automatic will not only give you a much faster follow-up shot, it also allows you to stay focused on your target, optic and the trigger, instead of having to manually operate a bolt-action rifle; all subsequent rounds are chambered by the rifle itself during the gas or blowback operation of the action.

The weapon easily disassembles like the standard AR for quick and easy cleaning and reassembly. The piston system drastically reduces fouling, and no venting means no holes for dirt and other contaminants to enter the system.

The full-length Picatinny rail on the receiver will allow you to mount scopes, lights, lasers, bipods, bayonets, etc. The adjustable cheek rest stock option is an added upgrade free bonus.

The innovative Noreen Bad News 338 Lapua provides tactical marksmen with the performance of a powerful and proven long range cartridge with the numerous advantages of the venerable AR platform. The Noreen 338 Lapua weighs only 13 pounds, and it vastly outperforms comparable bolt-action sniper rifles. This rifle comes with a custom muzzle-break and semi-auto action that significantly suppresses recoil. In the AR tradition, the Bad News 338 Lapua disassembles quickly for easy cleaning, then reasembles with no loss of zero. The familiar fit and feel of a conventional AR rifle makes the transition to the more powerful sniper rifle seamless. This Noreen includes an ultra-heavy duty Plano case, which is far superior to a pelican style case. 100% Made in the USA.
